data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous APIs via an opt-in flag (`CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncOverAsync`). **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All synchronous LINQ operators and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

**Every method in your repository breaks:**

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

## Migration

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key steps:**
1. **Remove** any `EnableSyncOverAsync` / sync-opt-in configuration — the option no longer exists and will cause a build error.
2. Convert all repository methods to `async Task<T>` and use the `Async` LINQ extensions (from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore`).
3. Propagate `async/await` up through callers (controllers, services, etc.) — this is typically the bulk of the work.
